land":"Stromberg, Kreuznach, Rhineland, Prussia","nameMeanings":[{"name":"von","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Vaughan  .","Chinese: variant of   Wong  .","Cambodian: written វ៉ុន, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Vaughan","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>fychan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Gisela","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’ or ‘scion’.  See  <b>Giselle</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"Giselle","meanings":["name of Frankish origin, from the Germanic word <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’. It was a common practice in medieval Europe to leave children as pledges for an alliance, to be brought up at a foreign court, and the name may be derived as a byname from this practice. This was the name by which the wife of  Duke Rollo  of Normandy (  <i>c.</i>860– <i>c.</i>930 ) was known. On her account the name enjoyed considerable popularity in France from an early period. Use of the name in English-speaking countries is much more recent, and is due mainly to the ballet Giselle (first performed in  1841 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Gisela von Schalksberg was born about 1107, in Germany as the daughter of Wedekind I von Schalksberg. She married Hermann von Stromberg about 1130. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1167, at the age of 61."},"et":{"um 1107–1167":"umbes 1107–1167","1107–1167":"1107–1167","1101–1162":"1101–1162","1127–1162":"1127–1162","1130–Male":"1130–Surnud","1132–Male":"1132–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1080–1140":"1080–1140","1080":"1080","1107":"1107","1127":"1127","ABT 1130":"umbes 1130","1167":"1167","1101":"1101","1132":"1132","1130":"1